---
import Page from '../layouts/Page.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE, SITE_DESCRIPTION } from '../consts';
---

<Page
	title="About"
	description={`Learn why ${SITE_TITLE} exists, how I research our guides, and how I keep recommendations honest.`}
	image="/images/about.jpg"
	breadcrumbs={[
		{ label: 'Home', href: '/' },
		{ label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
	]}
	showNewsletter={true}
>
	<h2>Why This Site Exists</h2>
	<p>
		{SITE_TITLE} started with a simple frustration: walking into a pet store and seeing dozens of feeding bowls, feeders, and accessories, with no clear guidance on what was actually safe or useful. I wanted a place where pet owners could find honest, research-backed answers without wading through marketing claims.
	</p>
	<p>
		Every guide here is built the same way I would research a purchase for my own pet: dig into real user experiences, compare materials and safety standards, and check what veterinarians and animal behavior research actually say.
	</p>

	<h2>How I Research</h2>
	<ol>
		<li><strong>Start with real pet-owner problems</strong> — questions from forums, reviews, and veterinary client education materials.</li>
		<li><strong>Compare products against safety and usability standards</strong> — food-grade materials, stability, capacity, ease of cleaning, and breed-fit.</li>
		<li><strong>Cross-check health claims with veterinary sources</strong> — including AVMA, AAHA, WSAVA, veterinary journals, and board-certified specialist guidance.</li>
		<li><strong>Read verified customer reviews</strong> on Amazon, Chewy, Reddit, and specialist communities to spot long-term durability and real-world issues.</li>
		<li><strong>Update regularly</strong> when products change, new studies are published, or readers point out better options.</li>
	</ol>

	<h2>Sources I Trust</h2>
	<p>
		I am not a veterinarian. The health information on this site is compiled from publicly available veterinary and academic sources, including:
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li>American Veterinary Medical Association (AVMA)</li>
		<li>American Animal Hospital Association (AAHA)</li>
		<li>World Small Animal Veterinary Association (WSAVA) nutrition and health guidelines</li>
		<li>Peer-reviewed journals such as <em>Journal of the American Veterinary Medical Association (JAVMA)</em>, <em>Veterinary Evidence</em>, and <em>BMC Veterinary Research</em></li>
		<li>Board-certified veterinary behavior and nutrition references</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		Specific studies and guidelines are cited within each article so you can check the original source yourself.
	</p>

	<h2>Honesty &amp; Affiliate Disclosure</h2>
	<p>
		This site is reader-supported through affiliate links, which means I may earn a small commission if you buy something through a link on this site. Brands do not pay for placement, and commissions do not influence recommendations.
	</p>
	<p>
		Every product guide includes a clear <a href="/affiliate-disclosure/">affiliate disclosure</a>. I only recommend products I would consider for my own pet or confidently suggest to a friend.
	</p>

	<h2>About Me</h2>
	<p>
		Hi, I am the founder, researcher, and writer behind {SITE_TITLE}. I run this site independently, which means every article reflects my own research and judgment rather than an editorial committee or brand partnership.
	</p>
	<p>
		By day I am a product manager, and I share my home with a picky cat, so I spend way too much time thinking about bowls, feeders, and mealtime routines. That obsession turned into {SITE_TITLE} — a place where I turn scattered product advice and conflicting opinions into clear, research-backed feeding guides.
	</p>

	<h2>When to See a Veterinarian</h2>
	<p>
		The guides on this site are for educational purposes only. They are not a substitute for professional veterinary advice, diagnosis, or treatment. If your pet has a medical condition, sudden behavior change, or you are unsure about a feeding change, please consult a licensed veterinarian.
	</p>
</Page>
